course.name: UI Reviewer Course
course.title: UI Reviewer Course V2
course.description: In this course, you will learn how to become an effective UI reviewer and be trained to identify common user interface issues. Before taking the evaluation, you will be taught the principles and techniques needed to assess UIs accurately and consistently. There is a skill assessment at the end.

contents.body: **Welcome to Andromeda Reviewer Course.** In this course, you will learn to identify tasks using the Spec Doc, ensuring a 4+ score in **Visuals**, **Explicit Instruction Following**, and **Functionality** before tasks go to the customer. Your primary goal: provide **clear, helpful feedback** to help attempters improve + **fix tasks** if response can be fixed in ≤5 minutes raising a score from 2→4 or 3→4 + **Evaluate the Attempter's** You’ll review: * **Visuals** – Modern, responsive, production-quality design * **Explicit Instruction Following** – Features that are explicitly asked on the prompt are missing or are incorrectly implemented * **Features** – All required elements fully implemented and working You'll also learn when to fix vs. reject and how to raise the bar on quality across Andromeda. At the end of the course, we’ll assess your understanding of the material and your attention to detail. **Following prompt instructions is critical for this project! Most task fail because of this, please pay close attention** **🔎A More Detailed Guide to the Reviewer Workflow Can Be Found…** [**Here**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vS14SRgRM4RLmgsKBy--2lOpGAVHVLEA6Yg9NUIFnEfaCS8HJwkAsZhpOcpTBGwy4mvLLL4dPLdU_7Z/pub):

**NEW GUIDELINES FOR L0 REVIEWS** In this Review Level, reviews will have a new focus, they will be quick and will aim to quickly identify and filter out any tasks which are bad. Reviews should take less than 45 minutes overall, and should be covered in the following way. In this reviews, we are **NOT Reviewing the Code beyond a quick skim for obvious rule violatons**. Just focus on this 3 key things: 1. **Audit the task (10 minutes):** Use the[ **Andromeda UI Spec Doc**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vQGTsjd5QyFKI_Xh1xpKdaBsnhdn97mGGUlGAjl7lZ6fAvH9sjG3sW7Az7cbPRFFsPmkw1ve4Yc_gfA/pub) and **ONLY** focus on **Visuals, Feature Completeness, and Functionality.** 2. **Provide Feedback (10 Minutes)** : Offer specific, actionable feedback to the attempter, regardless of your verdict (Approve, Fix & Approve, or Reject). 3. **Fix the task (5 minutes)** - If the task is fixable, fix it under 5 minutes. * **Approve** if it scores 4 or 5 across all dimensions. * **Fix and Approve** if minor issues can be fixed in ≤5 minutes, make the necessary changes that raise a score from 2→4 or 3→4 * **Reject** if it's fundamentally broken or not fixable in time (score 3 or below). [**A guide to help you identify rejectable, fixable, and acceptable tasks can be found here.**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vTkvYCWcNqu-v2zQd2gf8k9Rxm72r1t9vHFJ5Tc2r1U4xF5JscIpMM40saVgV80cSU7YxOqyTzYz34H/pub)

# **Step 1: Audit the Task** Your first critical step is a thorough audit. Always use the [Andromeda UI Spec Doc ](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vQGTsjd5QyFKI_Xh1xpKdaBsnhdn97mGGUlGAjl7lZ6fAvH9sjG3sW7Az7cbPRFFsPmkw1ve4Yc_gfA/pub)for quality control. **1. Understand Prompt Requirements:** * **Read carefully:** What did the attempter aim to create? * **List specifics:** Note every feature or instruction. Use the prompt rubric tool as a checklist. * **Verify language:** Was a coding language clearly stated? Its absence is a major flag. * **Confirm alignment:** Does the prompt fit our project's Use Case and required Programming Language (Nextjs, React/Typescript, HTML/CSS/JS)(see [QC Rubrics | Task Requirements Rubric](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vQGTsjd5QyFKI_Xh1xpKdaBsnhdn97mGGUlGAjl7lZ6fAvH9sjG3sW7Az7cbPRFFsPmkw1ve4Yc_gfA/pub))? **2. Evaluate UI Quality (WebAppQuality Rubric):** * **Visuals**: Is it modern, consistent, and responsive (adapts to screen sizes)? Are details polished? Avoid trademarked logos/Lucide React Icons. [**Familiarize yourself with the design guide here for more detail on what to watch out for.**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vQ0rYMr4lFLkczPIM7VbaGunA8EkHyhLR9BV9QImVHs-EW3JUAFtCgihtb8Ob3NbvYKZKArj6MEpFJb/pub) * **Features:** Are all requested and essential "common sense" features present and functional? (Dummy buttons for completeness are okay if not explicitly requested to work.) **3. Check Common Errors:** * **This is the most important step of the review process.** You should spend the majority of your time as a reviewer carefully examining the UI for the following major error categories. [**Refresh yourself on the common errors found here.**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vR9jGDjyPoJqfQ9sMIdC_9R0tRB6sICUEkBmkrvZLTu4thQJy1cnAzbQCnRvPWRv4OTPYrVkslfdKwZ/pub) * **Poor visual appearance:** [use the quick-fail guide here to help you](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vQaJY-8Yqx90weAxJZf-svKlnpGUtZrBDpG2lOaHsq6EZz3NagmmepaqmcKZgzkA_pR0b304dsTBBby/pub) * **Lack of functionality:** Missing any single feature or style explicitly requested in the prompt. (Use [this app](https://ui-req-gen.vercel.app/generate-requirements) for comparison). Examples include: Missed instructions, prohibited logos/icons, missing language specification, and any personal info. * **Broken features:** Any feature in the UI does not work to full functionality * **Inclusion of features that were not requested** * **Unpolished code:** As defined by the [WebAppQualityRubric](https://ui-req-gen.vercel.app/generate-requirements) Based on this audit, in the next step, you will form an initial decision: Approve, Fix and Approve, or Reject.

**Conditions for Accepting (or Fixing & Approving):** * **Scores 4 or 5 on all Rubric dimensions (Visuals, Code, Features)** after any quick fixes. * All **explicit functionality** from the prompt **is present and works**. * **Reasonably satisfies a user,** even if not completely perfect. * **Minor issues are fixable** within task timeframe. **Conditions for Rejecting:** * **Too much to fix:** Once issue is found, fix would take longer than 75 minutes. * **Fundamentally broken:** Requires a total visual redesign or is too broken to fix quickly. * **Missing core features:** Many main requested features are absent; adding them takes too long. * **Poor visuals:** Design is very basic/low quality and extensive time is needed to improve. * **Functionality missing:** Most UI functions don't work and are too time-consuming to fix. * **Low quality score:** Even after quick fixes, scores 3 or less on key rubric dimensions. **Reason for Rejecting:** **Hard to read text in dark mode,** **Using emojis is not professional** [UI LINK 1](https://scale-cds-public-us-west-2.s3.amazonaws.com/63fe4e654667d0a6f128105c/TMJG3j9Tjju8SKd) [UI LINK 2](https://scale-cds-public-us-west-2.s3.amazonaws.com/63fe4e654667d0a6f128105c/zU8MQp6i4snXXEz) **Conditions for Fixing:** * **Possible fixes:** If your fixes can bring the task up to a 4, go ahead and spend up to 75 minutes making those improvements. * **Missing features:** If any features are missing, you should add them if it takes less than 75 minutes. * **Minor functionality issues:** Core features work, or problems are fixable. * **High-impact, low-effort changes:** Easy changes that significantly improve visual appeal or usability. * **A few quick fixes can make a big difference for the user experience:** Task will be clean and functional enough after improvements. * **Improves approval rates:** Fixing issues instead of rejecting helps.

sections.title: Quality Score Rubric - What does it mean

contents.body: **This is your guide to assigning reviewer scores.** Accurate scoring is vital. Use the [Andromeda UI Spec doc ](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vQGTsjd5QyFKI_Xh1xpKdaBsnhdn97mGGUlGAjl7lZ6fAvH9sjG3sW7Az7cbPRFFsPmkw1ve4Yc_gfA/pub)to evaluate tasks. **Aim for a 4 or 5 score on all dimensions *after* any fixes.** **Here is the scoring field:**

The spec doc contains detailed information on the rating rubric. Below is a high-level overview of how to evaluate a task. We also recommend reviewing the [**Common Mistakes**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/10s3GO5SXbDimC1-M0OtGh-E7eO1MeL69XXjk67HP7Bw/edit?tab=t.onv0klx9cvy9#heading=h.32ti6zkkhenl) tab to stay aware of issues that attempters frequently overlook | **Score** | **What does it mean** | **Detailed Criteria** | **Example Scenario** | | --- | --- | --- | --- | | **1 – Unusable / Fails Task** | Fundamentally broken or unusable. Multiple critical failures across all dimensions. | \- UI is broken or completely outdated
- The code has syntax errors and does not run
- Instruction following is poor; key parts of the prompt are ignored
- Features are missing or incorrect
- Major inaccuracies in Code comments
- Contains chatbot-y or plagiarized content | The prompt asks for a login page. The output is a jumbled, table-based layout that doesn’t render; the code crashes; only a heading is present. | | **2 – Poor Quality** | Runs but with significant flaws. Poor alignment with prompt and quality expectations. | \- UI is dated or poorly styled
- Code runs with visible errors or broken parts
- Instructions are only partially followed
- Multiple features are incomplete or error-prone
- Minor to major comment inaccuracies
- Visual issues like unaligned elements, bad spacing | A job card UI renders with broken spacing, misaligned buttons, and missing required inputs. Code runs, but the layout is inconsistent, and the prompts were only half-followed. | | **3 – It does the job, but its not good enough to send to the customer** | Mostly meets requirements. Usable, but lacks polish or has minor flaws. | \- UI looks fine, but generic
- Code runs without crashing but uses some outdated patterns (e.g. React 17)
- **All key instructions followed**
- Minor visual or layout issues
- All core features are present | A functional contact form that responds well on desktop, misses responsive tweaks for mobile, and uses untyped props in TS. | | **4 – Good / Near Production-Ready** | Well-implemented and clean. Minor polish issues only. | \- UI is clean, modern, and responsive
- Code uses modern HTML5/React18/ES6+ practices
- All explicit instructions were followed accurately
- Optional asks may be thoughtfully included
- Clear and helpful comments with no major issues
- Includes all required features, and UI is visually appealing | A modern pricing table component that adjusts to screen sizes, uses useState, and includes styled call-to-action buttons, all features implemented. | | **5 – Stellar Quality Tasks**
(Makes you Proud to show off your work!!!) | Exemplary across all dimensions. Teaching example. | \- Visually exceptional UI with modern design, responsiveness, and accessibility
- Code is idiomatic, maintainable, and uses the latest standards
- Every instruction, even optional ones, followed
- All required and complementary features implemented
- Clean comments with no inaccuracies
- Can be used in real-world apps; contains thoughtful additions that work | A dashboard UI that auto-adjusts to screen size, has micro-interactions, reusable components, well-typed TS, and is perfectly aligned with the prompt—even added extras like dark mode or tooltips |

## **Step 1: Code Execution Check** **Action:** Test if the submitted code runs without critical errors. **Evaluation Criteria:** * Code executes without syntax errors? * Application loads without crashing? * No missing dependencies that prevent functionality? **Decision:** * **If all criteria are met (Yes):** Proceed to Step 2 * **If any criterion is not met (No):** Assign **score = 1**, provide detailed feedback explaining the execution failure (e.g., "Syntax error on line 23", "Missing React import"), and submit the review. **Reasoning for Score 1:** If the code doesn't run, the submission is fundamentally unusable regardless of other qualities.

## **Step 2: Core Functionality Verification** **Action:** Verify that the primary requested features are present and functional. **Evaluation Criteria:** *  All explicitly requested features are implemented? *  Primary features work as intended when tested? *  No critical functionality is completely missing? **Decision:** * **If all criteria are met (Yes):** Proceed to Step 3 * **If any criterion is not met (No):** Deduct **3 points** from final score, provide detailed feedback explaining missing/broken features (e.g., "Login form missing password field", "Submit button doesn't work"), and proceed to Step 3.

## **Step 3: Instruction Following Assessment** **Action:** Compare the submission against the prompt requirements. **Evaluation Criteria:** * Uses the correct technology stack specified in prompt? *  Follows format requirements (single file vs. multiple files)? *  Implements requested styling/design approach? *  Adheres to any explicit constraints mentioned? **Decision:** * **If all criteria are met (Yes):** Proceed to Step 4 * **If any criterion is not met (No):** Deduct **2 points** from final score, provide detailed feedback explaining instruction violations (e.g., "Used Vue instead of React", "Created multiple files when single file requested"), and proceed to Step 4.

## **Step 4: UI Quality and Responsiveness Check** **Action:** Assess the visual quality and responsive behavior of the interface. **Select one of the following options:** **Option A - Fully Responsive and Polished:** * Desktop view works perfectly * Mobile view works perfectly * UI looks professional and modern **Option B - Primary View Good, Minor Issues:** * Desktop works well, mobile has minor issues * OR UI looks good but has small visual problems **Option C - Significant UI Problems:** * Mobile completely unusable * OR major visual issues (broken layout, unreadable text) * OR looks very outdated/unprofessional **Decision:** * **If Option A:** Proceed to Step 5 * **If Option B:** Deduct **1 point** from final score, provide detailed feedback on specific issues, and proceed to Step 5 * **If Option C:** Deduct **2 points** from final score, provide detailed feedback on major UI problems, and proceed to Step 5

## **Review Conclusion** **Action:** 1. Calculate final score: **5 - (all deductions)** 2. Compile comprehensive feedback detailing: * Code execution issues from Step 1 * Missing/broken functionality from Step 2 * Instruction violations from Step 3 * UI/responsiveness problems from Step 4 **Output:** Completed review with final score and detailed feedback.

## **Quality Assurance Notes** * Use browser dev tools to test responsiveness across device sizes * Actually click/interact with all features to verify functionality * Check network tab for error messages during testing * Provide specific, actionable feedback with examples * Base scores on ONLY objective, testable criteria * Document evidence for each deduction made

* **Be honest about the scoring: If the task would still score a 3 or lower in Visuals, or Features even after quick fixes, be honest and score it accurately. Don’t inflate ratings—tasks are audited regularly, and inaccurate scoring may lead to flags or removal.**

Your feedback guides attempter improvement. Always provide written feedback, whether approving, fixing, or rejecting. Effective feedback is the cornerstone of quality and growth. As a reviewer, your insights are critical to helping creators improve their work and fostering a high-standard environment. To ensure your feedback is impactful, please use the following principles as a guide. [**Three Principles of Effective Feedback**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vR9FRoLJb0biem4Bm8c964dakmKzOG80zgAsH8HNTPAl-rjgxOl5PqHO-FbL3wFdD_BrZip8pHq_MdR/pub) Feedback must be: 1. Accurate: Double-check the[ ](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1g80IZ65YQ8heJu4gtJ7rE5OL1WyJwaMA8cB3Ci_ofus/edit?tab=t.7ej594sqz7z0)[project rubric and instructions.](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vQGTsjd5QyFKI_Xh1xpKdaBsnhdn97mGGUlGAjl7lZ6fAvH9sjG3sW7Az7cbPRFFsPmkw1ve4Yc_gfA/pub) Norms can vary between projects, so ensure your guidance is current and project-specific. 2. Specific: Avoid vague terms like "good" or "bad." Make your feedback actionable. Pinpoint exact areas for improvement. For example, instead of "needs more detail," say, "The 'About Us' section should elaborate on the company's mission and values, ideally in 3-4 sentences." 3. Constructive: Maintain a polite and helpful tone. Remember, contributors will read your comments directly. Frame suggestions positively to encourage learning. **This is what the feedback field looks like:** ****

**<mark data-color="rgb(126, 211, 33)" style="background-color: rgb(126, 211, 33); color: inherit">Good Example:</mark>**

“*You've done a great job with the visual concept and "techy" aesthetic, which are strong positives. However, to get this approved, you'll need to address several critical issues: the **"played games history" feature is incomplete***, *lacking full library viewing and visible effects when adding games; the **bar graph's Y-axis cuts off numbers over $5 million***, *impacting readability; there's **no mobile navigation menu***, *making the app largely unusable on smaller screens; and finally, **fundamental elements like the date picker and earnings icons are invisible when creating a new gig, alongside numerous glitchy animations** that detract from overall polish. Please tackle these points comprehensively in your next iteration.”*

<mark data-color="rgb(245, 162, 172)" style="background-color: rgb(245, 162, 172); color: inherit">Bad Example:</mark>

“*Task needs work, it has not met instructions in the prompt. Read the instructions carefully”*

You’re now moving into the assessment phase. Pay close attention to the prompt, most mistakes happen by overlooking what’s being asked. Your answers will determine whether you receive reviewer permissions. Here’s a quick summary of key points to remember. As a reviewer, you will: 1. **Review** the [Common Errors ](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vTDn1Vz_oEzMAtVrKslKxBFmFnES2s8GZ-qOvGLnQlVBs_qgYwVolnZMYGyAcarKMFCfE9P1aPaWyMt/pub)to stay aware of issues that attempters frequently overlook 2. **Audit tasks** against the Andromeda UI Spec (Visuals, Code, Features) 3. **Use** this [checklist](https://docs.google.com/document/d/10s3GO5SXbDimC1-M0OtGh-E7eO1MeL69XXjk67HP7Bw/edit?tab=t.kpnjtmgtuw5l) to assess Tasks 4. **Score them** using our [Quality Rubric](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vQaJY-8Yqx90weAxJZf-svKlnpGUtZrBDpG2lOaHsq6EZz3NagmmepaqmcKZgzkA_pR0b304dsTBBby/pub) 5. **Decide** whether to Approve, Fix & Approve, or Reject Tasks 6. **Provide actionable feedback** that helps contributors improve
